While reading Ramanujan's Collected Papers I came across a nice formula which he mentions without proof $$	an^{-1}(e^{-\pi x/2}) =  rac{\pi}{4} - \left(	an^{-1} rac{x}{1} - 	an^{-1} rac{x}{3} + 	an^{-1} rac{x}{5} - \cdotsight)$$ where $x$ is any real number. Ramanujan proves similar formulas with terms involving $	an^{-1}(x^{2})$ but leaves the above one as if it is obvious. I tried to simplify RHS term by term starting with $$ rac{\pi}{4} - 	an^{-1}x = 	an^{-1} rac{1 - x}{1 + x}$$ and then  egin{align} RHS &=  rac{\pi}{4} - 	an^{-1}x + 	an^{-1} rac{x}{3}
otag\ &= 	an^{-1} rac{1 - x}{1 + x} + 	an^{-1} rac{x}{3}
otag\ &= 	an^{-1}\left(\dfrac{\dfrac{1 - x}{1 + x} + \dfrac{x}{3}}{1- \dfrac{1 - x}{1 + x}\cdot\dfrac{x}{3}}ight)
otag\ &= 	an^{-1}\left(\dfrac{3 - 2x + x^{2}}{3 + 2x + x^{2}}ight)
otag\ \end{align} My guess is that the argument of $	an^{-1}$ probably looks like some convergent to a suitable continued fraction expansion of $e^{-\pi x / 2}$ but I am just not able to figure it out. An obvious difficulty is that any expansion of $e^{-\pi x / 2}$ as a continued fraction would involve $\pi$ as well as. Please suggest any other approach to prove the Ramanujan's formula. Update : If I differentiate with respect to $x$ I get the LHS as $$ rac{-\pi e^{-\pi x / 2}}{2(1 + e^{-\pi x})}$$ and the RHS comes out to be $$-\left( rac{1}{1 + x^{2}} -  rac{3}{3^{2} + x^{2}} +  rac{5}{5^{2} + x^{2}} - \cdotsight)$$ This is similar to the partial fraction expansion of $	anh(x)$ given by $$ rac{	anh x}{8x} = \sum_{k = 1}^{\infty} rac{1}{(2k - 1)^{2}\pi^{2} + 4x^{2}}$$ but not exactly as desired. For the proof of formula for $	anh x$ see this .

